\title{Tree IDs}

\p{In [[forester]], each tree has an ID, given by the name of the file
for a 'top-level' tree, or using the notation \code{\subtree[TREEID]{...}}
for 'subtrees'. These IDs are unique, and are used for creating links
in the forest. For more information, please see the Forester documentation
on [tree address](https://www.forester-notes.org/0073/index.xml). You
may also find [this document](https://www.forester-notes.org/0052/index.xml)
to be a useful introduction and overview of the Forester system.}


\p{By default, trees in our forest are assigned a unique sequential ID in the form
\code{stt-XXXX}, where \code{XXXX} is a four digit [base 36 number](https://www.forester-notes.org/0074/index.xml) – i.e. consisting of
the alphabet \code{0123456789ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ}.
}

\p{There are two exceptions to this rule:
\ul{
\li{Trees with the taxon \em{reference}, living in \code{trees/ref/}, should be
named either using the initials of the authors and the year, or with a name if
it is a reference to a software project.}

\li{Trees with a taxon \em{person}, living in \code{trees/people}, should be
given the name of the person all in lower case, no separator between words.}
}
}

\p{When multiple people are working on the project at the same time, it is
infeasible to keep these IDs unique and sequentially ordered, and so we have
a process to make assigning correct IDs as simple as possible.
}

